Routines driver software exports to the rest of the world:

  Used by anything that wants to send a link to a map.

    route_to_url( $map_start, $map_end, @waypoints )
	Return a URL suitable for generating a map of routes from the
	starting address (or coordinates) to the ending points
	via the waypoints.

  Used by anything that wants to create a map file (vs. just a link)

    progress( $title, @input_ps )
	Return a string containing the resulting map or other formatted
	graphical information file (e.g. kml, gpx etc) based on the
	the listed stops and implied routes.

  Used to determine most efficient route:

    order_query( $first_stop, @waypoints, $last_stop )
	Get the most efficient path from the first to the last stop
	but not necessarily in order of the waypoints specified.
	Note that his may not actually encompass the entire route
	as we have the ability to prescribe the stops done at start and
	the stops done at the end.  We only use this to re-order stops
	in between.

    expected( @addresses )
	Return a list of lat,lon strings of not only the addresses, but
	also points along the path between those addresses, preferably
	on roads, and preferably the quickest possible path between the
	two points (though NOT changing the order of the points).  This is
	still getting flushed out.

  Experimental to figure out how big routes should be given a limited number
  of drivers.  These routines are called with chunks of addresses by
  upper level software that doesn't care how the information is retrieved
  (so we could use different sources if, say, Mapquest goes under).

    geocode_batch( @addresses )
	Return a list of latitude,longitude coordinates corresponding
	to the provided list of addresses.

    costs_batch( $starting_from_address, @rest_of_addresses )
	Return a list of costs corresponding to the distances between
	the first argument and the rest.  The first element of the list
	will always be zero.
